<subSubSection id="C328F2FFFF8ACB00479773E5FDE0FA0B" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8DA174FF8ACB00479773E5FA28FA97" blockId="47.[151,1437,1051,1509]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
Remarks: The status of a separate species has been recognized by Martin &amp; Davids (2004) for populations of 
<taxonomicName id="4C32DAF7FF8ACB0047C77381FE62FB07" authority="Besseling, 1942" authorityName="Besseling" authorityYear="1942" box="[151,453,1231,1257]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setosus">
<emphasis id="B9467D66FF8ACB0047C77381FEADFB06" box="[151,266,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">H. setosus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA3DC85FF8ACB0046407381FE62FB07" author="Besseling, A. J." box="[272,453,1231,1257]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="2 - 6" refId="ref72881" refString="Besseling, A. J. (1942) Nederlandsche Hydrachnidae. Genus Hygrobates. Entomologische Berichten, 11 (243), 2 - 6." type="journal article" year="1942">Besseling, 1942</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, a taxon over a long time considered a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C32DAF7FF8ACB0043167381FAB0FB07" authorityName="Lebert" authorityYear="1879" box="[1094,1303,1231,1257]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigromaculatus">
<emphasis id="B9467D66FF8ACB0043167381FAB0FB07" box="[1094,1303,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">H. nigromaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- for details see also 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA3DC85FF8ACB0047A873BDFE7DFAE3" author="Martin, P. &amp; Dabert, M. &amp; Dabert, J." box="[248,474,1267,1293]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="347 - 360" refId="ref75913" refString="Martin, P., Dabert, M. &amp; Dabert, J. (2010) Molecular evidences for species separation in the water mite Hygrobates nigromaculatus Lebert, 1879 (Acari, Hydrachnidia): evolutionary consequences of the loss of larval parasitism. Aquatic Sciences, 72, 347 - 360. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00027 - 010 - 0135 - x" type="journal article" year="2010">
Martin 
<emphasis id="B9467D66FF8ACB00461C73BDFE22FAE3" box="[332,389,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">et al.</emphasis>
(2010)
</bibRefCitation>
. Recently, PeÅ¡iÄ 
<emphasis id="B9467D66FF8ACB0045C973BDFD75FAE3" box="[665,722,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">et al.</emphasis>
(2020) published two further related species from the Balkans, showing that 
<taxonomicName id="4C32DAF7FF8ACB00467F7259FDA6FADF" authorityName="Lebert" authorityYear="1879" box="[303,513,1303,1329]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigromaculatus">
<emphasis id="B9467D66FF8ACB00467F7259FDA6FADF" box="[303,513,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">H. nigromaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents a more diversified species group. Obviously, also many Italian records given above require re-investigation. However, in view of the characteristics of their collecting sites, at least for the specimens from the large prealpine lakes it is probable that they represent in fact 
<taxonomicName id="4C32DAF7FF8ACB0043747211FB51FA97" authorityName="Lebert" authorityYear="1879" box="[1060,1270,1375,1401]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigromaculatus">
<emphasis id="B9467D66FF8ACB0043747211FB51FA97" box="[1060,1270,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">H. nigromaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A275C01DFF8ACB0043AC7211FA2BFA97" box="[1276,1420,1375,1401]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" sensu="stricto">sensu stricto</taxonomicNameLabel>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8DA174FF8ACB00479772CDFCB2FA73" blockId="47.[151,1437,1051,1509]" box="[199,789,1411,1437]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Habitat: Lenitobiont. Large streams, littoral of lakes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8DA174FF8ACB00479772E9FDE0FA0B" blockId="47.[151,1437,1051,1509]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
Distribution: Palaearctic? In view of the new data concerning 
<taxonomicName id="4C32DAF7FF8ACB00442372E9FBE4FA2F" authorityName="Lebert" authorityYear="1879" box="[883,1091,1447,1473]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigromaculatus">
<emphasis id="B9467D66FF8ACB00442372E9FBE4FA2F" box="[883,1091,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">H. nigromaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like mites, all distribution data from the 20 
<superScript id="7C470C3CFF8ACB00464A7284FE80FA36" attach="left" box="[282,295,1482,1496]" fontSize="6" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">th</superScript>
century are questionable.
</paragraph>
